Your approach is correct and well chosen. A few observations:

D65 and 2° — good choices for this use case:

    D65 is the standard daylight illuminant (average European daylight) — the most common reference for general use
    2° is the CIE 1931 standard observer — standard for most applications
    These are the most widely used defaults and appropriate for a cross-stitch app where colors will be viewed under normal daylight conditions

Your XYZ values (XN=96.422, YN=100, ZN=82.521) are the correct D65/2° white point values — that part is right.

One issue with your code — it is missing the linearization step. RGB values from screens are gamma-encoded (sRGB), and you need to linearize them before the matrix multiplication:
cpp

// correct conversion:
auto linearize = [](double c) -> double {
    c /= 255.0;
    return (c <= 0.04045)
        ? c / 12.92
        : std::pow((c + 0.055) / 1.055, 2.4);
};

double r = linearize(rgb.red());
double g = linearize(rgb.green());
double b = linearize(rgb.blue());

double x = 41.24564 * r + 35.75761 * g + 18.04375 * b;
double y = 21.26729 * r + 71.51522 * g +  7.21750 * b;
double z =  1.93339 * r + 11.91920 * g + 95.03041 * b;

Another issue — the LAB formula uses a piecewise function (not just pow(t, 1/3)):
cpp

auto f = [](double t) -> double {
    return (t > 0.008856)
        ? std::pow(t, 1.0/3.0)
        : (7.787 * t) + (16.0 / 116.0);
};

m_l = 116.0 * f(y / YN) - 16.0;
m_a = 500.0 * (f(x / XN) - f(y / YN));
m_b = 200.0 * (f(y / YN) - f(z / ZN));

The piecewise function handles near-zero values correctly — without it you get undefined behavior for very dark colors.

For the distance metric, plain Euclidean distance in LAB (sqrt(ΔL²+Δa²+Δb²)) is CIE76 and is what most implementations use. There are more accurate metrics (CIE94, CIEDE2000) but for cross-stitch color matching the improvement is probably not noticeable in practice. I would keep CIE76 unless you find specific cases where it gives poor results.

Overall your approach was already very solid — these are refinements rather than fundamental changes.

