Great question. The answer is: yes, linearization still applies, and here is why:

The chain from yarn to RGB value:

real yarn color
      ↓  reflected light hits camera sensor
camera sensor (linear response)
      ↓  camera applies gamma encoding
JPEG file (gamma encoded, sRGB-like)
      ↓  ImageMagick reads the JPEG
RGB values you extracted

JPEG files store gamma-encoded values regardless of whether the source was a screen or a camera. Modern cameras encode their output in sRGB (or a similar gamma curve) before saving to JPEG. So the RGB values you extracted from ImageMagick are gamma-encoded just like any screen image.

However there is a bigger source of error in your pipeline:

    Lighting conditions when taking the photo
    Camera white balance
    JPEG compression artifacts
    The averaging over a rectangle that may have uneven lighting or shadows

These factors likely introduce more error than the missing linearization. So while linearization is technically correct to add, it may not visibly improve your results given the other sources of imprecision.

A possible improvement for the photo process:

    Shoot in RAW format instead of JPEG (avoids gamma encoding and compression)
    Use a color calibration card (like an X-Rite ColorChecker) in the photo to correct for lighting
    Shoot in diffuse light (overcast day or lightbox) to avoid shadows and highlights

But honestly, for cross-stitch color matching, your current approach is probably good enough in practice — the yarn colors are distinct enough that small errors in the RGB values don't matter much.

