Here is a clear explanation of linearization and the ColorChecker:

Linearization — why it matters:

RGB values in images use gamma encoding so that the distribution of values is perceptually linear — more bits are devoted to darker shades since humans are more sensitive to them. This means the raw RGB numbers are not physically proportional to light intensity.
Matt77hias

The important thing is that sRGB is not a sensible place to do math. You can't add sRGB numbers together or blend them. Before doing any math, you have to convert to linear space first.
Medium

The exact formula to linearize (sRGB → linear):
cpp

auto linearize = [](double c) -> double {
    c /= 255.0;
    return (c <= 0.04045)
        ? c / 12.92
        : std::pow((c + 0.055) / 1.055, 2.4);
};

The formula uses two parts glued together — a straight line near zero and an exponential curve for higher values. The cutoff point 0.04045 was chosen so the two parts connect smoothly.
Entropymine

Does it apply to your photos?

JPEG files save images in the gamma-corrected sRGB color space
MathWorks
— this applies whether the source was a camera or a screen. So yes, linearization applies to your photos.

On the ColorChecker:

An X-Rite ColorChecker is a card with 24 color patches whose exact LAB values are known. The workflow is:

    Place it next to your yarn card when photographing
    Load the photo and measure the RGB values of the ColorChecker patches
    Compare them to the known reference values
    Compute a correction matrix that maps your measured values to the correct ones
    Apply that matrix to the rest of the photo

Tools like darktable (free, open source) can do this automatically if you shoot in RAW. For JPEG it is harder but still possible with tools like ArgyllCMS.

However given that your current colortable already gives satisfying results in practice, this is probably more effort than it is worth for you. The linearization fix is simpler and more worthwhile.